{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656658","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656658"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:36+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:16:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.4,0.12,0,0.44,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80377"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11488"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7593"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"8485"},{"type":"tags","id":"10475"},{"type":"tags","id":"10507"},{"type":"tags","id":"10508"},{"type":"tags","id":"10513"},{"type":"tags","id":"11389"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80377"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe proximal tubule of the nephron performs several important functions in maintaining homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes proximal tubular secretion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reabsorption of filtered substances","Passive diffusion along concentration gradients","Transport between tubular cells only","Active transport from blood to tubular lumen","Movement of water via osmosis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism is \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive transport from blood to tubular lumen\u003C/strong\u003E. Proximal tubular secretion involves the movement of substances from peritubular capillaries across tubular cells into the lumen using specific transport proteins that require energy in the form of ATP. This allows the kidney to eliminate substances even against concentration gradients.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion along concentration gradients\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretion often occurs against concentration gradients and requires energy\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMovement of water via osmosis\u003C/strong\u003E - Water movement occurs via osmosis but this is not secretion\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReabsorption of filtered substances\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes movement in the opposite direction, from lumen to blood\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport between tubular cells only\u003C/strong\u003E - Secretion involves movement from blood to lumen, not between cells\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EImportant substances secreted by the proximal tubule include organic anions (like penicillin and para-aminohippuric acid), organic cations, and hydrogen ions for acid-base regulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The proximal tubule actively secretes organic anions and cations from peritubular capillaries into the tubular lumen via specific transport proteins.","Secretion allows rapid elimination of waste products and toxins from the blood, even against concentration gradients.","Proximal tubular secretion is important for maintaining acid-base balance through hydrogen ion secretion."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T15:05:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T15:07:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11488"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80377"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type"